On Mon, Jan 2, 2012 at 6:41 AM, Narasimha PVR Rao <pvr@...> wrote:

> Namaste,
>
> I visited someone's pradosha pooja when I visited Texas last week. The
> pooja was very nice and sincere and I loved it, but I noticed one bad
> practice and honestly told them what I thought. I want to share the same
> with all of you.
>
> Showing deepam or lamp to the lord is one of the upacharas (services)
> performed in the pooja after the abhishekam (bathing). In some
> traditions, they show multiple lamp setups with multiple numbers of
> wicks, each setup with a specific mantra. While the abhishekam and
> upacharas were going on, I was sitting with eyes closed and meditating
> with Gayatri mantra. After the showing of various lamps, I felt
> something negative and opened my eyes. I saw that one person was
> forcibly extinguishing the fire in each wick with a rose petal.
>
> God knows if the idol or Shiva lingam used in a pooja has divine
> presence or not, but live moving fire DOES have god in it. It is not at
> all a good idea to extinguish fire forcibly. If keeping tens of wicks
> burning is not practical, put very little oil in each wick so that it
> lights for a small time only. If you can't wait, then don't light so
> many wicks. Just light 1-5 wicks and show them with all mantras. That is
> far better than showing a lamp with 21 wicks, another lamp with another
> number of wicks and so on and then forcibly extinguishing all the tens
> of wicks. Even if an auspicious material like rose petal is used to
> press and extinguish, that does not make it acceptable.
>
> Best regards,
> Narasimha
